The code snippet you provided in the comments is standard Android Java code for managing **Fragments**.

Specifically, it performs two main actions:
1.  **Retrieves** a reference to a container view in your layout (identified by `R.id.fragment_container`).
2.  **Replaces** whatever content is currently in that container with a new instance of a `Fragment`, then commits that change.

Here is the cleaned-up version of that logic with proper indentation:

```java
// Find the container in the layout where the fragment will be placed
// .getSupportFragmentManager() is used when working with AppCompatActivity
FragmentManager fragmentManager = getSupportFragmentManager();

// Find the specific container view by ID
ViewGroup container = (ViewGroup) fragmentManager.findFragmentById(R.id.fragment_container); 
// Note: Usually, we don't cast the result of findFragmentById to ViewGroup directly unless 
// we are manipulating the view itself. Usually, we just use the ID for the transaction.

// Start a transaction to replace the content
fragmentManager.beginTransaction()
    .replace(R.id.fragment_container, new Fragment()) // Replace content with new Fragment
    .commit(); // Commit the changes
```

### How to use this in a real project

If you want to use this in an actual Android application, here is a complete example within an `Activity`:

```java
import androidx.appcompat.app.AppCompatActivity;
import androidx.fragment.app.Fragment;
import androidx.fragment.app.FragmentManager;
import androidx.fragment.app.FragmentTransaction;
import android.os.Bundle;

public class MainActivity extends AppCompatActivity {

    @Override
    protected void onCreate(Bundle savedInstanceState) {
        super.onCreate(savedInstanceState);
        setContentView(R.layout.activity_main);

        // Check if the container is empty to avoid re-adding fragments on rotation
        if (savedInstanceState == null) {
            loadFragment(new YourCustomFragment());
        }
    }

    private void loadFragment(Fragment fragment) {
        FragmentManager fragmentManager = getSupportFragmentManager();
        FragmentTransaction transaction = fragmentManager.beginTransaction();

        // R.id.fragment_container must match the FrameLayout ID in your XML layout
        transaction.replace(R.id.fragment_container, fragment);

        // Optional: Add to back stack so the user can press "Back" to return to previous state
        // transaction.addToBackStack(null); 

        transaction.commit();
    }
}
```

**Required XML Layout (`activity_main.xml`):**
For this code to work, your layout file must contain a container (usually a `FrameLayout`) with the matching ID:

```xml
<FrameLayout xmlns:android="http://schemas.android.com/apk/res/android"
    android:id="@+id/fragment_container"
    android:layout_width="match_parent"
    android:layout_height="match_parent" />
```
